Nu t√¶ller vi total antal ord sagt pr karakter pr stykke. Dern√¶st omregnet til procent af totale ord i stykket.


# count words in "spoke"
(plays %>% 
  # remove rows that are not dialogue and empty speakers
  filter(!is.na(spoke), speaker != "") %>%
  
  # select only the columns, that we are interested in
  select(speaker, title, year, spoke) %>% 
  
  # add the number of spoken words
  mutate(n_spoken_words = str_count(spoke, '\\w+')) %>% 
  # remove the spoken words
  select(-spoke) %>%
  
  # group by title and speaker
  group_by(title, year, speaker) %>% 

  # Sum the words spoken by each speaker in each play
  # Lastly store the new data frame in a new reference for later use
  summarise(words = sum(n_spoken_words), title, year) %>%
    distinct() -> my_summary
)
   # Calculate %
(my_summary %>%
    ungroup(speaker) %>%
    summarise(words_play = sum(words)) -> totals)
   
(my_summary %>%
  full_join(totals) %>%
  summarise(freq = words / words_play, speaker, title, year, words, words_play) ->
    new_summary
    )
  # Sort by freq
(new_summary %>%
  arrange(desc(freq)))

Now ‚Äúnew_summary‚Äù holds all the information that we need. We sorted it to see who speaks the most. Next we choose a character to visualise‚Ä¶ In this example I choose ‚ÄúJeronimus‚Äù.

Visualisering

character_plot <- function(character_name) {
  new_summary %>% 
  filter(speaker == character_name) %>%
  arrange(year) %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = title, y = freq, x = title)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    theme(legend.position="bottom") +
    labs(
      title = "Procent talte ord over √•r og komedier",
      subtitle = toupper(character_name),
      caption = "Kilde: DSL"
    ) +
  xlab("year") +
  ylab("Procent sagte ord") +
  facet_wrap(~year, ncol=nrow(new_summary), switch="x") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())
}

Et trick til at f√• stykkerne til at st√• i √•rsr√¶kke

Indenfor statistik arbejder man med noget, som p√• engelsk hedder factor. Jeg mener, at det p√• dansk hedder faktor. Det er n√•r man har en variabel eller observation, som kan tage v√¶rdier, der ikke er sorterbare i sog selv. Fx en farve. Her kan man s√• selv angive v√¶rdiernes r√¶kkef√∏lge.

Dette kan vi udnytte til sortering af titel. Jeg laver f√∏rst en liste med alle de anvendte titler og sorterer den efter √•rstallet. Derefter omformer jeg titel kolonnen til en faktorvariabel og angiver der den r√¶kkef√∏lge som jeg fik fra sorteringen efter √•rstal.

summary %>% 
  filter(speaker %in%   c("henrik", "jeronimus", "leander")) %>% 
  #mutate(title = str_c(title, " ", year)) %>% 
  distinct(title) %>% 
  arrange(year) %>% 
  pull(title) -> factor_levels
